    "analysis": "Executor results reviewed: global thresholds (P95/P5) were computed for candidate services using full-series data, then telemetry was filtered to the incident window 2024-02-24 23:16:45 → 23:46:45 UTC. Findings: ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, and ts-travel-service all show short-lived anomalies (typically 2 consecutive points > global P95) across multiple KPIs (cpu, diskio, mem, latency, socket, workload) and on log.row_count / trace row_count/duration. ts-train-service shows no anomalies. A trace-based localization query that looked for direct 'to_ts-'/'from_ts-' style relationships involving these specific service names returned no matches, so we cannot use trace call-chains to pick the most-downstream faulty service. Given multiple service-level faults and absent usable trace relationships, I applied the fallback rule: choose the service-level fault with the most significant deviation from its global threshold and consider earliest occurrence. Comparing severity and timing: ts-order-service CPU breached its P95 by the largest relative margin (~78%) with the earliest breach at ~2024-02-24T23:19:00+00:00 (ts-route CPU also breached at 23:19 but with smaller relative severity; ts-auth breaches occur slightly later). Log.row_count and trace row_count increases across services cluster later (~23:25–23:26) and likely reflect downstream/backpressure. Error logs are empty. Therefore, the combined evidence (earliest anomalous time, largest relative threshold breach on CPU, correlated latency and increased row_count) indicates ts-order-service as the root cause component with resource (CPU) pressure as the primary failure reason. This diagnosis follows the required preprocess → anomaly detection → fault identification → root cause localization flow and adheres to the rule of using metric severity and timing when traces cannot disambiguate.",
